text:
Seventh Avenue, adjoining and at the S. W. corner of Central Park South (W. 59th St.J, showing pavement condition relative to subway construction here. To the left are buildings occupied by the Central Park Riding Academy. The Seventh Avenue entrance to Central Park is at the right. Note the crosstown street car on Central Park South. This thoroughfare is actually W. 59th Street, changing it's name
where it borders the Park.
June 4, 1915.
Borough President of Manhattan
No. 668
title: Manhattan: 7th Avenue - Central Park South

text:
Seventh Avenue, at the south east corner of Central Park South (W. 59th Street). To the right is a portion of the Madrid, a unit of the Central Park Apartments. This structure was replaced in 1928 by the present New York Athletic Club. To the left is the Seventh Avenue entrance to the southerly portion of Central Park.

June 4, 1915.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 677

text:
Central Park South, north side, west from 7th Avenue, to Columbus Circle. Shown at the right is the southwesterly corner of the Park.

June 4, 1915.

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 672

Central Park South (West 59th Street), west from Seventh Avenue, showing prominently pavement conditions on the north side of this thoroughfare. Central Park is to the right.

June 19, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 764
Central Park South, west from Seventh Avenue. June 19, 1915

Central Park South (West 59th Street), south side, west from Seventh Avenue. At the right appears a portion of Central Park. This view extends to Columbus Circle. Note beyond that point shadowy outline of the St. Paul the Apostle R. C. Church.

June 18, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 762

Central Park South, east from 7th Avenue. To the left appears a portion of the Park; same being its southern extremity. In the background on Fifth Avenue prominently appears the Hotel Netherland. At this point this thoroughfare regains its original identity, 59th Street. To the right are units of the Central Park Apartments Buildings. (Spanish Flats)

June 4, 1915

Borough President of Manhattan
No. 675

Central Park South ( W. 59th Street), west from 7th Avenue. The photographers vantage point is the north side of this thoroughfare, actually the southern extremity of the Park, and he is viewing towards Columbus Circle.

June 4, 1915.

170-160 Central Park South (West 59th Street) adjoining the S.E. corner of Seventh Ave., showing the site of the 45-story Essex House being cleared. Photographer is viewing southward through clearance and shows structures on the south side of West 58th Street. This set consists of a negative and a positive.

September 14, 1928.

F. M. Demarest.
